column1: 235045;instagram;2018-11-08 11:21:52;FALSE;"one week to go!!! one week today my book it's no secret
who would have thought that it could be achieved?
certainly not me for the last 44 years!
i had always used words effectively and wanted to write a book to inspire others
column2: but fear stopped me from doing anything about it until july 2017.
fear of success and a fear of ridicule.

column1: whilst working with sharon bott on a life changing course dna light up concieved by melanie pledger  i filled in my workbook and asked myself the question 'what's stopped me?' at that moment i committed to my goal and wrote down ' i can write
column2: i can achieve it '. i spent an hour cutting and pasting a pictorial representation of my inner potential
column3: my golden light which fills my heart and mind.

column2: here we are one week from launch!

column2: without #authorsandco abigail horne and her fabulous team and my rock charlie downey for believing in me before i believed in myself.

column1: we all have unlimited potential if we chose to seek it out and believe that we can be so much more.

column1: 235100;instagram;2018-11-08 12:54:59;FALSE;breaking the silence|this is for that little boy living in the shame of being sexually abused. this is for the women too afraid to seek help. for the little girl seeking direction after being raped but instead she is silenced in fear of being shamed. this is for anyone who has kept the pain & guilt bottled up inside.... this is your day to come and that first step to freedom. i was sexually abused from the age of 5-11 years old. i blamed myself and felt guilty about what happened to me. but on today i have taken back my joy & my peace. you do not have to live in shame. what was done to you was not your fault. you are not alone. speak your truth. as you speak it

column1: it even smells like a street
there's a bar at the end
where i can meet you and your friend
i smell the blood of les tricoteuses
but there's a shop on the corner
so you scream out of line
i want you! i need you!
well on the street where you live
i could not hold up my head
for i put all i have in another bed
on another floor in the back of a car
in the cellar like a church with the door ajar
well i guess we've must be looking for a different kind
but we can't stop trying till we break up our minds
till the sun drips blood on the seedy young knights
who press you on the ground while shaking in fright
i guess we could cruise down one more time
we'll buy some drugs and watch a band
then jump in a river holding hands

column2: often with much risk of criticism and 'gas lighting.' its fearless champion is bhanwari devi. while living in a rural farming community

when my fiancÃ© and i first met
column2: he asked me out on to a bar with a few friends. typical
column3: right? after a few drinks i needed to use the restroom. also typical. so far the night was going well
column4: the bar wasn't busy and i was having a good time. however that changed quickly. as i turned the corner
column5: there was a man leaving the men's restroom
column6: and he waved at me.  thinking nothing of it
column7: i put up my hand to wave back.  at that point
column8: he grabbed my arm and pinned me up adainst the wall that was a few feet from us
column9: and demanded that i kissed him. i repeatedly told him no
column10: and was unable to break free from his grip. why i didn't take more extreme measures to break free (like racking him) i'll never know. a few moments later
column11: another man comes around the corner and i was relieved. i thought surely this new stranger would see what was happening and come to my rescue
column12: but i couldn't have been more wrong. he began telling me ""why don't you just kiss him? give him what he wants"". at this point i was terrified. thoughts of kidnapping and rape started to cross my mind. i was frozen and couldn't even bring myself to call out for help.  at that point
column13: a third man came around the corner. this time it was my fiancÃ© and he calmly told them to back off. the other two men left and i shot into the bathroom as quickly as i could. i couldn't believe what just happened.

column1: this happened during one of my most emotionally unstable points in my adult life
column2: so for months i continued to ask myself what i did wrong for that scene to unfold. finally i realized that i did nothing wrong. i don't care if he had been drinking
column3: as he clearly knew what he was doing
column4: along with his friend who encouraged the assault.

column1: 235529;instagram;2018-11-08 21:02:20;FALSE;"you'll hear a lot of people mostly { cough } kinksters {  cough cough cough }
say rape and abuse can be hot and how they wanna be raped and abused.  they tell rape and abuse victims just how hot it is and how they are just ""  so lucky "" to gave gone through that.
there is nothing hot about being traumatized for your whole life!
there is nothing hot about never feeling safe again!
there is nothing hot about people shaming you day in and day out because you were the victim of a monster.
there is nothing sexy about wanting to kill yourself because you feel ruined thanks  to victim blamers.
rape and abuse aren't sexy or hot.
by saying its sexy and sexualizing those things you normalize it and promote those horrible acts.

in the last few days being both a full time student and a full time entrepreneur has been draining and challenging. you would hope that while building a business that looks to end sexual violence you would not face much push back and red tap; but unfortunately that seems to be the case.
doing both is a constant juggling act that requires check ins with my advocates

however! i have some exciting news to share with everyone tomorrow on behalf of safepod. so look out for a video tomorrow that will be a call to action. a beautiful way for the city to come together and demand change. ""safety doesn't happen by accident"" is a saying i've recently adopted. so stay tuned until tomorrow to see safepod's exciting plan.

column1: 235569;instagram;2018-11-08 21:50:31;FALSE;"#fbf to just last sunday... so i have been back and forth as to whether to post this or not but it has been bugging me all week. to be honest i haven't given the #metoo movement much thought as for as long as i can remember i have been subjected to unwanted advances from men and have always thought well i am asking for it. you see i am a flirt (ask any of my friends and my hubby and they will 150% agree!) i love to dress up and feel good about myself and my body and sometimes even have a little bit too much on show. so i have always thought oh well i do ask for these unwanted advances. but last week i woke the eff up and really understood this #metoo hashtag. i was out after the races with my friends and husband and some seedy guy brushed his crotch up against me and slyly grabbed my ass. i froze the just walked off and told a gentleman that we had lunch with and he then opened up the conversation about his wife and 16 yr old daughter and their experiences and his conversations with them about #metoo. i was like oh yes but look i am wearing a tight dress with my boobs pushed up it's expected & i am asking for it and he said ""but we have been with you all day and have any of us once made an inappropriate pass?! it's not ok. but how does that change?"" later on i told my husband and his friends and naturally they wanted to find this guy
column2: me not wanting to start anything ignored it again but then while dancing with my husband two guys started to use me like a stripper pole and both my husband and friend were seeing red. i got out off the dance floor and sat down for the rest of the night being cautious not to start any trouble with shane and his friends. on the way home i was angry with him for getting so angry but after taking a day or so to think about it i have realised it's not ok. my night ended up hiding in a corner because i thought i had asked for trouble wearing this dress out around drunk men. but they aren't men they are revolting pigs that make women feel ashamed. i have been out 3 times the last few weeks & haven't been subjected to this. the real men that i have met haven't once touched me inappropriately or made unwanted sleezy comments. cont below...";;en;#FBF

column1: 235586;instagram;2018-11-08 22:20:40;FALSE;"don't practice until you get it right. practice until you can't get it wrong.
i know alot of us may be use to the saying ""practice makes perfect"" but i will never forget the day that my professor told me otherwise.
he told me ""practice makes permanent and perfect practice makes perfect
column2: and i was caught off guard but then i realized that he was completely right.

column1: when i teach classes i keep this in mind and i try my very best to make sure that every one of you gets the technique right.
it may be far from perfect at first
column2: but with every class i like to revisit previous techniques
column3: so that it becomes  muscle memory. if a day ever comes
column4: where you need to use the technique
column5: my hope is that you won't freeze in panic
column6: but know exactly what to do to survive.

column1: i will be having our next class november 18th at 9:30 am

let me tell you why. iâ€™m in my fourth and final year of law school (fourth because i am also in business school) and i am currently writing my â€œwriting requirementâ€ at the law school which basically equates to a thesis. i presented on this thesis yesterday and that slide you see pictured above was my concluding statement.

but lets backtrack a bit. i thought long and hard a couple months ago about what iâ€™d dedicate an entire semester of research/writing to and what iâ€™d like that end product to look like/mean. i decided to write this thesis through a class with one of my favorite professors. this class? sexuality law. this was the first elective in all my law school â€œcareerâ€ that was not business based. i took the course to expand my wealth of knowledge and immerse myself in an area completely foreign to me. but then again
column2: i wanted to somehow sew my business law self into this mix to make this experience as valuable as possible. iâ€™m passionate about the #metoo movement and fueled by activists like  @rosemcgowan @milano_alyssa and many other fighters. i wanted to somehow tie sexuality law to business law and i found a topic perfect for me back in august. i decided to analyze the recent senate bill put forth by california seeking to protect #metoo movement victims by prohibiting ndas/confidentiality agreements in regards to claims about sexual harassment
column4: and discrimination based on sex. i wonâ€™t go into my opinions here because thatâ€™s something iâ€™d only share with those truly interested about the topic...but today i had the experience of a lifetime relating to all of this. (mind you

column1: 235633;instagram;2018-11-08 23:45:27;TRUE;;"even if you don't sign petitions - sign this petition.
#letherspeak this is an important one. gagging survivors of sexual assault from speaking out is hugely problematic and sends the message that they have no agency
column2: no control over their own stories and their own lives
column3: just as they had no choice in what was done to them. it protects predators and silences survivors. yet section 194k of the crimes act does precisely that. the laws in tasmania and nt
column4: which state that sexual assault survivors cannot speak out and cannot appear in media or be named even with the survivorâ€™s full consent
column5: must come into line with other states
column6: to reflect a survivorâ€™s right to tell her or his own story if they choose. please consider signing the petition here: https://www.megaphone.org.au/petitions/let-her-speak

column1: to understand how shockingly unjust this law is
column3: and why she wants to speak out
column4: here: https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/let-her-speak-shocking-reason-woman-cant-tell-her-sexual-assault-story/news-story/718ad770a25833970f961c551f3eaab1 (i hate having to call her jane doe. itâ€™s not her name and she doesnâ€™t want to be known as jane doe. the law prevents me from giving her the dignity of her own identity.) this is just one horrific story among many.

column1: see also: 'let sexual assault victims speak: tara moss calls for change to tasmanian law' (link in the bio) please consider supporting this campaign
column2: which has been designed by nina funnell in partnership with end rape on campus and marque lawyers

235646;instagram;2018-11-08 23:54:23;FALSE;during my junior year of high school, my ex-boyfriend once choked me in the middle of the hallway against a locker during a transition to the next class. i remember random students walking past and thinking that it was a joke because i tired my best to not react as if he was hurting me. i felt so embarrassed that he was my boyfriend at that moment. i was embarrassed to say that i loved this person. after that experience, i remember making excuses for his aggressive behavior towards me. telling myself that he was only lashing out because he didn't know how to cope with his anger and he needed me to help him. i thought i could fix him. a year later, with the girl he had been cheating on me with. i herd that he had hit her in the face during an argument, bruising her left cheek and i was not surprised. she stayed with him. swearing it was the only time something like that had happened but i knew better. looking back now i am glad that he cheated and left me. as scarring as the experience was, i am lucky it happened to me. i realized that i could never rewrite years of pain with only a few months of trying to love him enough for the both of us. i think that women who have experienced or are currently experiencing ipv are strong but they are scared to speak out. i commend them for their strength for staying but i also hope that one day they escape and realize what i realized three years ago, i deserve better. thank you for reading. please know this is a true experience and we appreciate the opportunity to share with you guys. i hope you find it as inspiring as we did. ğŸ’œ please comment any thoughts below. #metoo #ipv #relationshipviolence #speakupspeakout  #terpsagainstipv;;en;#metoo, #ipv, #relationshipviolence, column1: 235875;instagram;2018-11-09 06:09:46;FALSE;"last thing i'll post on this subject.  i was a lucky one.  only once
column3: and no physical bruises.  i had told him to stop a couple of times and told him he was hurting me.  i also cried.  that is what i felt most ashamed about.  i wasn't strong enough to stop it from happening and felt like i didn't do enough of anything except cry.  i felt disgusted and used and angry.  i never reported anything because i had given consent before this night.  he's married and has kids. i'm married and have kids.  i don't think he'd ever do something like that again but obviously i didn't know him as well as i thought i did.  i pushed this night to the back of my mind
column4: or so i thought.  john knows about that night.  he knows details no one else ever will.  he had to know as i needed to hear out loud that my ""no"" and ""stop"" would be respected if it came to that.  when the #metoo movement started i ignored it.  my sexual assault didn't seem ""bad enough"" to talk about and my life was great.  when the kavanaugh stuff started happening i realized how much that night really had stuck with me.  memes about rape were being posted on facebook and our country's leaders were mocking assault victims.  i was ending the night in tears feeling defeated and conversations with john were coming up again.  this time we were discussing consent and teaching our kids to respect the words ""no"" and ""stop"" as it seems like that is the only power we have.  to influence the next generation to get rid of this rape culture as i feel like our generation is lost.  i didn't know how much i'd be triggered by comments of family and friends who could talk about rape as if it was just a fantasy and not reality.  i type all this to say that my experience that i didn't think was ""bad enough"" still caused an emotional breakdown years later.  if you are someone who also was triggered by all of this and has silently kept your experience to yourself
column5: just know that you're not alone.  i stand with you and i believe you.  honestly
